###### Abstract

We study the problem of learning a single neuron with respect to the \(L_{2}^{2}\)-loss in the presence of adversarial distribution shifts, where the labels can be arbitrary, and the goal is to find a "best-fit" function. More precisely, given training samples from a reference distribution \(p_{0}\), the goal is to approximate the vector \(\bm{w}^{*}\) which minimizes the squared loss with respect to the worst-case distribution that is close in \(\chi^{2}\)-divergence to \(p_{0}\). We design a computationally efficient algorithm that recovers a vector \(\hat{\bm{w}}\) satisfying \(\mathbb{E}_{p^{*}}(\sigma(\hat{\bm{w}}\cdot\bm{x})-y)^{2}\leq C\,\mathbb{E}_{ p^{*}}(\sigma(\bm{w}^{*}\cdot\bm{x})-y)^{2}+\epsilon\), where \(C>1\) is a dimension-independent constant and \((\bm{w}^{*},p^{*})\) is the witness attaining the min-max risk \(\min_{\bm{w}\,:\,\|\bm{w}\|\leq W}\max_{\bm{p}}\mathbb{E}_{(\bm{x},y)\sim p}( \sigma(\bm{w}\cdot\bm{x})-y)^{2}-\nu\chi^{2}(\bm{p},p_{0})\). Our algorithm follows a primal-dual framework and is designed by directly bounding the risk with respect to the original, nonconvex \(L_{2}^{2}\) loss. From an optimization standpoint, our work opens new avenues for the design of primal-dual algorithms under structured nonconvexity.

## 1 Introduction

The problem of learning a single neuron from randomly drawn labeled examples is a fundamental problem extensively studied in the machine learning literature. Given labeled examples \(\{(\bm{x}_{i},y_{i}):(\bm{x}_{i},y_{i})\in\mathbb{R}^{d}\times\mathbb{R}_{i=1} ^{N}\}\) drawn from a reference distribution \(p_{0}\), the goal in this context is to recover a parameter vector \(\bm{w}_{0}^{*}\) that minimizes the squared loss \(\Lambda_{\sigma,p_{0}}(\bm{w})\) over a ball of radius \(W>0\):

\[\bm{w}_{0}^{*}:=\operatorname*{arg\,min}_{\bm{w}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}:\|\bm{w}\| _{2}\leq W}\Lambda_{\sigma,p_{0}}(\bm{w});\quad\Lambda_{\sigma,p_{0}}(\bm{w}) :=\mathbb{E}_{(\bm{x},y)\sim p_{0}}(\sigma(\bm{w}\cdot\bm{x})-y)^{2},\] (1)

