### Distributional Assumptions

Similar to [14], we make two assumptions about the target distribution of the covariates (\(p_{\bm{x}}^{*}\)). First, we assume that the optimal solution \(\bm{w}^{*}\) satisfies the following "margin-like" condition:

**Assumption 2.1** (Margin).: _There exist absolute constants \(\lambda,\gamma\in(0,1]\) such that \(\mathbb{E}_{\bm{x}\sim p_{\bm{x}}^{*}}[\bm{x}\bm{x}^{T}\mathbb{I}_{\bm{w}^{*} \bm{x}\geq\gamma\|\bm{w}^{*}\|_{2}}]\succeq\lambda\bm{I}\), where \(p_{\bm{x}}^{*}\) is the \(\bm{x}\)-marginal distribution of \(p^{*}\)._

We also assume that \(p_{\bm{x}}^{*}\) is subexponential with parameter \(B\), which is an absolute constant.

**Assumption 2.2** (Subexponential Concentration).: _There exists a parameter \(B>0\) such that for any \(\bm{u}\in\mathcal{B}(1)\) and any \(r\geq 1\), it holds that \(\Pr_{\bm{x}\sim p_{\bm{x}}^{*}}[|\bm{u}\cdot\bm{x}|\geq r]\leq\exp(-Br)\)._

Appendix E of [14] shows that Assumptions 2.1 and 2.2 are satisfied by several important families of distributions including Gaussians, discrete Gaussians, all isotropic log-concave distributions, the uniform distribution over \(\{-1,0,1\}^{d}\), etc.

For simplicity, we assume the labeled samples \((\bm{x}^{(i)},y^{(i)})\) drawn from the reference distribution are bounded. This assumption, which does not affect the approximation constant for Problem 1.3, only impacts iteration and sample complexities. We state the bound on the covariates below, while a bound on the labels follows from prior work (Fact 2.6 stated in the next subsection).

**Assumption 2.3** (Boundedness).: _There exists a parameter \(S\) such that for any fixed \(\bm{u}\in\mathcal{B}(1)\) it holds that \(\bm{u}\cdot\bm{x}\leq S\) for all sample covariates \(\bm{x}\) in the support of \(\widehat{p}_{0}\)._We also assume without loss of generality that \(\|\bm{w}^{*}\|_{2}^{2}\geq C\operatorname{OPT}+\epsilon\) for some absolute constant \(C\), since otherwise \(\bm{0}\) would be a valid \(O(\operatorname{OPT})+\epsilon\) solution. Algorithmically, we can first compute the empirical risk (per Corollary C.3) of the output from our algorithm and of \(\hat{\bm{w}}=\bm{0}\) and then output the solution with the lower risk to get an \(O(\operatorname{OPT})+\epsilon\) solution; see Claim E.2 for a detailed discussion.

