### Upper Bound on the Gap Function

Having obtained a lower bound on the gap function, we now show an upper bound, leveraging our algorithmic choices. The proof is rather technical and involves individually bounding \(L(\bm{w}_{i},\widehat{\bm{p}}^{*})\) above and bounding \(L(\bm{w}^{*},\widehat{\bm{p}}_{i})\) below to obtain an upper bound on the gap function, which equals \(L(\bm{w}_{i},\widehat{\bm{p}}^{*})-L(\bm{w}^{*},\widehat{\bm{p}}_{i}).\) We state this result in the next lemma, while the proof is in Appendix D.

**Lemma 3.3** (Gap Upper Bound).: _Let \(\bm{w}_{i},\widehat{\bm{p}}_{i},a_{i},A_{i}\) evolve according to Algorithm 1, where we take, by convention, \(a_{-1}=A_{-1}=a_{0}=A_{0}=0\) and \(\bm{w}_{-1}=\bm{w}_{0},\)\(\widehat{\bm{p}}_{-1}=\widehat{\bm{p}}_{0}.\) Assuming Lemma 2.5 applies, then, for all \(k\geq 1,\sum_{i=1}^{k}a_{i}\mathrm{Gap}(\bm{w}_{i},\widehat{\bm{p}}_{i})\) is bounded above by_

