## Appendix A Related Work

Learning Noisy NeuronsThe problem of learning noisy neurons has been extensively explored in recent decades; notable works include [11, 12, 13]. In the recent past, the focus has shifted towards specific activation functions such as ReLUs, under both easy noise models such as realizable/random additive noise [11, 12] and more difficult ones like adversarial label noise [10, 11, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 18].

Even with clean labels, this problem has exponentially many local minima when using squared loss [1]. Unfortunately, directly minimizing the squared loss using (S)GD on a bounded distribution does not converge to the global optimum with probability 1 [12]. Even so, gradient based methods can achieve suboptimal rates in the agnostic setting (\(\sqrt{\mathrm{OPT}_{0}}\) vs \(\mathrm{OPT}_{0}\)) for distributions with mild distributional assumptions [13]. Making slightly stronger assumptions on the marginal does allow us to get efficient constant factor approximations. [10] developed an efficient learning method that is able to handle this in the presence of adversarial label noise and for isotropic logconcave distributions of the covariates. This was later extended to broader classes of activation functions and under weaker distributional assumptions by [10, 11, 12]. Without specific distributional assumptions, learning remains computationally difficult [10, 11]. The challenges extend to distribution-free scenarios with semi-random label noise, where methods like those in [10] address bounded noise, and [12] and [12] explore stricter forms of Massart noise in learning a neuron with noise. In this paper, we consider the harder setting of distributionally robust optimization, where an adversary is allowed to impose not only errors in the labels, but also adversarial shifts in the underlying distribution of the covariates.

Distributionally Robust OptimizationDistributional mismatches in data have been extensively studied in the context of learning from noisy data. This includes covariate shift, where the marginal distributions might be perturbed, [1, 13, 15], and changes in label proportions [16, 17, 18]. This research also extends to domain adaptation and transfer learning [1, 18, 19, 20, 21]. Distributionally robust optimization (DRO) has a rich history in optimization [1, 10] and has gained traction in machine learning [1, 1, 18, 19, 20, 21], showing mixed success across applications like language modeling [20], class imbalance correction [21], and group fairness [17].

Specifically this has also been studied in the context of linear regression and other function approximation [1, 18, 20]. Typically, DRO is often very sensitive to additional sources of noise, such as outliers ([17, 18, 19]). However, prior work makes strong assumptions on the label noise as well as requiring convexity of the loss. We study the problem of learning a neuron where the labels have no guaranteed structure, effectively studying the setting for a combination of two notions of robustness -- agnostic learning as well as covariate shift.

